<LENGTH>
<P>
328 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Daryl Kelley 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 LAKIN LEGACY: A featured achievement of Chancellor Thomas G. Lakin was 
spending more money on the county's community college district stepchild, 
Oxnard College. . . . So a day after the youthful chancellor died suddenly, 
that college mourned: "How can such a horrible thing happen to such a nice 
person?" instructor Carmen Eblen said. (B1). . . Lakin drew heat for his 
commitment to the Oxnard campus, but operated by a standard set by the Rev. 
Martin Luther King Jr.: "The ultimate measure of a man is not where he stands 
in moments of comfort and convenience, but where he stands during challenge and 
controversy." 
</P>
<P>
 FATHER AND SON: When Capt. Michael Porrazzo took command recently of the 
Ventura CHP office, he followed by 27 years his father's Ventura reign. . . . 
"There's a row of pictures of all the commanders that have ever been here. I 
recall coming down here and seeing my dad's picture on the wall. So it was sort 
of natural for me to move here," said Porrazzo, 47. . . . He and his deceased 
father, Harold Porrazzo, may be unique for the California Highway Patrol. "In 
my time, there's never been a commander who was followed by his son." 
</P>
<P>
 PARADISE REGAINED: Thirty years ago, when crime was low and schools were new, 
the San Fernando Valley was their refuge. Today, the children of those urban 
refugees are finding clear skies and safe streets in Thousand Oaks. (Valley 
Business, Page 10.) . . . "We could not be happier," resident Jeanine Price 
said. . . . And now, increasingly, the business world is seeking out the Conejo 
Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 MOTHER AND DAUGHTER: The mother was the first woman mayor of Santa Paula. The 
daughter will be the first woman city manager of Ventura. (B1) . . . Eleanor 
Crouch's daughter Donna Landeros, 46, will come home as a $105,000-a-year 
manager 28 years after she graduated from Santa Paula High. . . . "She wasn't 
one of those kids you had to nag to do her homework," said father Bill Crouch, 
a structural engineer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
